s across the world. TripHobo&rsquo;s trip planning platform serves as a one-stop destination for all the travel needs- exploring attractions, creating itineraries and booking hotels, transportation, and tours.<\\/p>\\n<p class=\\\"p1\\\">Users can now book their hotels, transportation, and tours from the portal. In order to propagate the thought of simple and care-free travel, we have adopted Shut Up N\' Travel as our official Travel thought.<\\/p>\\n<p class=\\\"p1\\\"><img src=\\\"\\/storage\\/uploads\\/00000000077.jpg\\\" alt=\\\"triphobo website\\\" width=\\\"625\\\" height=\\\"398\\\" \\/><\\/p>\",\"id\":\"26\"}',NULL,NULL,1,'2018-10-18 16:12:26','192.168.0.1','Mozilla/5.0 (Macintosh; Intel Mac OS X 10_13_6) AppleWebKit/537.36 (KHTML, like Gecko) Chrome/69.0.3497.100 Safari/537.36'),(357,'LOGIN','LOGIN',NULL,'directus_users',0,1,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0,'2018-10-18 16:12:43','103.81.243.2','Mozilla/5.0 (Macintosh; Intel Mac OS X 10_14_0) AppleWebKit/537.36 (KHTML, like Gecko) Chrome/69.0.3497.100 Safari/537.36'),(358,'ENTRY','UPDATE','24','projects',24,1,'{\"id\":\"24\",\"status\":\"1\",\"sort\":null,\"project_type_id\":\"3\",\"title\":\"PhonePass\",\"subtitle\":null,\"details\":\"<h2>PhonePass<\\/h2>\\n<p><strong>How does one craft a User Experience for device orientations in 6 degrees of freedom?<\\/strong><\\/p>\\n<p>PhonePass has a patent-pending algorithm to uniquely identify devices based on the hardware signature obtained by holding the device in six different very precise orientations &ndash; vertical facing you, vertical away from you, horizontal facing you, horizontal away from you, on its back, and on its face. The unique device determination is used in a multi-factor, multi-device security&nbsp;strategy.<\\/p>\\n<h3>Challenges for the User Experience<\\/h3>\\n<p>How can one get everyday users to do these complicated manoeuvres?<br \\/>Can we make this a fun and fast process?<br \\/>The lean approach: Experiment and Learn&nbsp;<br \\/>Before building the security solution, we identified the two MVP experiments that the PhonePass team should run.<\\/p>\\n<p>Test whether the UX is delightful and effective in obtaining the results?<br \\/>Test whether users can accomplish the task in a short time space, especially through repeated use?<br \\/>Additionally, the PhonePass team decided to add another experiment: Test whether their implemented algorithm yields unique device fingerprints?<\\/p>\\n<h3>The Solution<\\/h3>\\n<p>The most critical feature was to come up the alignment interaction: a way to guide users to align the device to only one of the X, Y and Z dimensions.<\\/p>\\n<p>Taking a cue from airplane horizon indicators, the elegant UX solution was to align the black border (which moves with one of the dimensions), the blue line (which moves with another dimension) with the red line which indicates the perfect center.<\\/p>\\n<p>A similar approach was used for the horizontal plane but with overlapping bubbles.&nbsp;<\\/p>\\n<p><img src=\\\"\\/storage\\/uploads\\/00000000068.jpg\\\" alt=\\\"phonepass_usage\\\" width=\\\"938\\\" height=\\\"975\\\" \\/><\\/p>\\n<p>A simple set of instructions told users what to do and vibration based feedback indicated when they had succeeded.<\\/p>\\n<p><img src=\\\"\\/storage\\/uploads\\/00000000067.jpg\\\" alt=\\\"phonepass_instructions\\\" width=\\\"1280\\\" height=\\\"720\\\" \\/><\\/p>\\n<h3>The Gamification<\\/h3>\\n<p>To motivate users to work this repeatedly and to provide enough statistical data for our experiments, we gamified the experiences and allowed users to compete against themselves in seeing how fast they could get all 6 readings done.<\\/p>\\n<p><img src=\\\"\\/storage\\/uploads\\/00000000069.jpg\\\" alt=\\\"phonepass_game\\\" width=\\\"837\\\" height=\\\"701\\\" \\/><\\/p>\",\"banner_image\":null,\"thumbnail\":\"66\"}','{\"details\":\"<h2>PhonePass<\\/h2>\\n<p><strong>How does one craft a User Experience for device orientations in 6 degrees of freedom?<\\/strong><\\/p>\\n<p>PhonePass has a patent-pending algorithm to uniquely identify devices based on the hardware signature obtained by holding the device in six different very precise orientations &ndash; vertical facing you, vertical away from you, horizontal facing you, horizontal away from you, on its back, and on its face. The unique device determination is used in a multi-factor, multi-device security&nbsp;strategy.<\\/p>\\n<h3>Challenges for the User Experience<\\/h3>\\n<p>How can one get everyday users to do these complicated manoeuvres?<br \\/>Can we make this a fun and fast process?<br \\/>The lean approach: Experiment and Learn&nbsp;<br \\/>Before building the security solution, we identified the two MVP experiments that the PhonePass team should run.<\\/p>\\n<p>Test whether the UX is delightful and effective in obtaining the results?<br \\/>Test whether users can accomplish the task in a short time space, especially through repeated use?<br \\/>Additionally, the PhonePass team decided to add another experiment: Test whether their implemented algorithm yields unique device fingerprints?<\\/p>\\n<h3>The Solution<\\/h3>\\n<p>The most critical feature was to come up the alignment interaction: a way to guide users to align the device to only one of the X, Y and Z dimensions.<\\/p>\\n<p>Taking a cue from airplane horizon indicators, the elegant UX solution was to align the black border (which moves with one of the dimensions), the blue line (which moves with another dimension) with the red line which indicates the perfect center.<\\/p>\\n<p>A similar approach was used for the horizontal plane but with overlapping bubbles.&nbsp;<\\/p>\\n<p><img src=\\\"\\/storage\\/uploads\\/00000000068.jpg\\\" alt=\\\"phonepass_usage\\\" width=\\\"938\\\" height=\\\"975\\\" \\/><\\/p>\\n<p>A simple set of instructions told users what to do and vibration based feedback indicated when they had succeeded.<\\/p>\\n<p><img src=\\\"\\/storage\\/uploads\\/00000000067.jpg\\\" alt=\\\"phonepass_instructions\\\" width=\\\"1280\\\" height=\\\"720\\\" \\/><\\/p>\\n<h3>The Gamification<\\/h3>\\n<p>To motivate users to work this repeatedly and to provide enough statistical data for our experiments, we gamified the experiences and allowed users to compete against themselves in seeing how fast they could get all 6 readings done.<\\/p>\\n<p><img src=\\\"\\/storage\\/uploads\\/00000000069.jpg\\\" alt=\\\"phonepass_game\\\" width=\\\"837\\\" height=\\\"701\\\" \\/><\\/p>\",\"id\":\"24\"}',NULL,NULL,1,'2018-10-18 16:19:53','103.81.243.2','Mozilla/5.0 (Macintosh; Intel Mac OS X 10_14_0) AppleWebKit/537.36 (KHTML, like Gecko) Chrome/69.0.3497.100 Safari/537.36'),(359,'FILES','ADD','1','directus_files',78,1,'{\"id\":\"78\",\"status\":\"1\",\"name\":\"00000000078.jpg\",\"title\":\"Nap 26\",\"location\":\"\",\"caption\":\"\",\"type\":\"image\\/jpeg\",\"charset\":\"binary\",\"tags\":\"\",\"width\":\"1280\",\"height\":\"583\",\"size\":\"235451\",\"embed_id\":null,\"user\":\"1\",\"date_uploaded\":\"2018-10-18 16:20:44\",\"storage_adapter\":\"local\"}','[]',NULL,NULL,1,'2018-10-18 16:20:44','103.81.243.2','Mozilla/5.0 (Macintosh; Intel Mac OS X 10_14_0) AppleWebKit/537.36 (KHTML, like Gecko) Chrome/69.0.3497.100 Safari/537.36'),(360,'ENTRY','UPDATE','19','projects',19,1,'{\"id\":\"19\",\"status\":\"1\",\"sort\":null,\"project_type_id\":\"2\",\"title\":\"CUDDLY\",\"subtitle\":\"Animal Welfare Website\",\"details\":\"<p>poundWISHES, now CUDDLY is an online crowdfunding platform that connects animal lovers with animal rescues and shelters. Technology is at the heart of the business. Ignite Solutions (my current workplace) are the UX &amp; technology partner for CUDDLY.<\\/p>\\n<p>Our first task was to bring stabilize the existing system. poundWISHES was handled by another firm earlier and we faced a lot of issues while working with the previous architecture and hence came up with a simple one-flow-at-a-time revamp plan.&nbsp;<\\/p>\\n<p>We recommended a multi-phased UX improvement and modernizing approach. The web interface was revamped to give the site a fresh look. We established detailed web and campaign tracking to give insights into donor behavior.&nbsp;<\\/p>\\n<p>Tighter and reliable integration with payment providers reduced reconciliation errors and streamlined the crowdfunding distribution.<\\/p>\\n<p>We embarked on a major initiative to bring in an innovative pet gift registry offering, the first of its kind. Donors could gift items to rescued pets rather than just cash. This offering has been a hit.&nbsp;<\\/p>\\n<p>Working with CUDDLY to introduce new features and improvise the experience as we now have a comparatively stable system.<\\/p>\\n<p>The client wanted to highlight the new feature on the homepage \\\"adopter registries\\\" and suggested a design but it failed to make users understand what it used to do or still does along with registries. Came up with a design which is a page which will divert the three types of users of Cuddly: Pet Parents, Donors, and Rescues.<\\/p>\\n<p><img src=\\\"\\/storage\\/uploads\\/00000000075.jpg\\\" alt=\\\"homepage_cuddly\\\" width=\\\"625\\\" height=\\\"635\\\" \\/><\\/p>\\n<p>&nbsp;<\\/p>\\n<p>Homepage designed to show what Cuddly is, what all it does for animal welfare without promoting any single module. Buttons for users to navigate to sub-landing pages. The purpose to this design was that CUDDLY stepped in \\\"registries\\\" along with donations and fundraising. One section celebrating happiness and other two were not joyful. To balance out these emotions, came up with a homepage which does not promote any module and gives equal space to Registries, Rescues and Donors. Therefore, no navigation bar is added until the user selects one of the three buttons.<\\/p>\\n<p>&nbsp;<\\/p>\\n<p>&nbsp;<\\/p>\",\"banner_image\":\"45\",\"thumbnail\":\"44\"}','{\"details\":\"<p>poundWISHES, now CUDDLY is an online crowdfunding platform that connects animal lovers with animal rescues and shelters. Technology is at the heart of the business. Ignite Solutions (my current workplace) are the UX &amp; technology partner for CUDDLY.<\\/p>\\n<p>Our first task was to bring stabilize the existing system. poundWISHES was handled by another firm earlier and we faced a lot of issues while working with the previous architecture and hence came up with a simple one-flow-at-a-time revamp plan.&nbsp;<\\/p>\\n<p>We recommended a multi-phased UX improvement and modernizing approach. The web interface was revamped to give the site a fresh look. We established detailed web and campaign tracking to give insights into donor behavior.&nbsp;<\\/p>\\n<p>Tighter and reliable integration with payment providers reduced reconciliation errors and streamlined the crowdfunding distribution.<\\/p>\\n<p>We embarked on a major initiative to bring in an innovative pet gift registry offering, the first of its kind. Donors could gift items to rescued pets rather than just cash. This offering has been a hit.&nbsp;<\\/p>\\n<p>Working with CUDDLY to introduce new features and improvise the experience as we now have a comparatively stable system.<\\/p>\\n<p>The client wanted to highlight the new feature on the homepage \\\"adopter registries\\\" and suggested a design but it failed to make users understand what it used to do or still does along with registries. Came up with a design which is a page which will divert the three types of users of Cuddly: Pet Parents, Donors, and Rescues.<\\/p>\\n<p><img src=\\\"\\/storage\\/uploads\\/00000000075.jpg\\\" alt=\\\"homepage_cuddly\\\" width=\\\"625\\\" height=\\\"635\\\" \\/><\\/p>\\n<p>&nbsp;<\\/p>\\n<p>Homepage designed to show what Cuddly is, what all it does for animal welfare without promoting any single module. Buttons for users to navigate to sub-landing pages. The purpose to this design was that CUDDLY stepped in \\\"registries\\\" along with donations and fundraising. One section celebrating happiness and other two were not joyful. To balance out these emotions, came up with a homepage which does not promote any module and gives equal space to Registries, Rescues and Donors. Therefore, no navigation bar is added until the user selects one of the three buttons.<\\/p>\\n<p>&nbsp;<\\/p>\\n<p>&nbsp;<\\/p>\",\"id\":\"19\"}',NULL,NULL,1,'2018-10-18 16:22:27','103.81.243.2','Mozilla/5.0 (Macintosh; Intel Mac OS X 10_14_0) AppleWebKit/537.36 (KHTML, like Gecko) Chrome/69.0.3497.100 Safari/537.36'),(361,'ENTRY','ADD','1','directus_files',79,1,'{\"id\":\"79\",\"status\":\"1\",\"name\":\"00000000079.jpg\",\"title\":\"nap26 thumbnail\",\"location\":\"\",\"caption\":\"\",\"type\":\"image\\/jpeg\",\"charset\":\"binary\",\"tags\":\"\",\"width\":\"852\",\"height\":\"807\",\"size\":\"183677\",\"embed_id\":null,\"user\":\"1\",\"date_uploaded\":\"2018-10-18 16:32:49\",\"storage_adapter\":\"local\"}','[]',NULL,NULL,1,'2018-10-18 16:32:49','103.81.243.2','Mozilla/5.0 (Macintosh; Intel Mac OS X 10_14_0) AppleWebKit/537.36 (KHTML, like Gecko) Chrome/69.0.3497.100 Safari/537.36'),(362,'ENTRY','ADD','27','projects',27,1,'{\"id\":\"27\",\"status\":\"2\",\"sort\":null,\"project_type_id\":\"3\",\"title\":\"Nap26\",\"subtitle\":\"Sleep, Recharge, Rejuvenate\",\"details\":\"<h2>Nap26<\\/h2>\\n<p>This audio program uses pulsating beats to create sound vibration which match natural sleeping patterns, signaling the brain to enter a more relaxed state. NAP26 wakes you after 26 minutes, researched as the optimum length of time for a powernap.<\\/p>\\n<p>&nbsp;<img src=\\\"\\/storage\\/uploads\\/00000000078.jpg\\\" alt=\\\"Nap 26\\\" width=\\\"1280\\\" height=\\\"583\\\" \\/><\\/p>\\n<p>&nbsp;<\\/p>\",\"banner_image\":null,\"thumbnail\":\"79\"}','[]',NULL,NULL,1,'2018-10-18 16:32:49','103.81.243.2','Mozilla/5.0 (Macintosh; Intel Mac OS X 10_14_0) AppleWebKit/537.36 (KHTML, like Gecko) Chrome/69.0.3497.100 Safari/537.36'),(363,'ENTRY','UPDATE','27','projects',27,1,'{\"id\":\"27\",\"status\":\"1\",\"sort\":null,\"project_type_id\":\"3\",\"title\"